{
  "text": "Once this convergence is achieved, several directions may be worth exploring. First, we may want to deduce directly proof theoretical results from superconsistency, without proving cut elimination first. Second, we may want to extend the notion of super-consistency to type theory. The recent [CITATION_1] that relates deduction modulo and type theory may be a good starting point.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "14751708"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "14751708": {
      "title": "Embedding Pure Types Systems in the lambda Pi-calculus modulo",
      "abstract": "The lambda-Pi-calculus allows to express proofs of minimal predicate logic. It can be extended, in a very simple way, by adding computation rules. This leads to the lambda-Pi-calculus modulo. We show in this paper that this simple extension is surprisingly expressive and, in particular, that all functional Pure Type Systems, such as the system F, or the Calculus of Constructions, can be embedded in it. And, moreover, that this embedding is conservative under termination hypothesis."
    }
  }
}